<subSubSection id="8107280620A6CF67B1016AD54FBEFB9C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="521D7BE1171CE2C8E5573E1374BE491E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="476969E4623BC15CDB4ECE1C9E2929B9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="777702C15FACC32B16AFF7EA162CD11B" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">USA</emphasis>
: MD.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="74F207E3A86766C2CC6888718C0BC90A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3920971656870FEB296B7174608022D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1748D287D407E9876328D8881A686770" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The specific name indicates the similarity of this species to its possible sister taxon, 
<taxonomicName id="F45BC13A058B3BA0E8D8EC35B582884B" authorityName="Hering" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia galii" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galii">
<emphasis id="FBD20B2D752C3C50E08D70337F89AA82" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia galii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which also feeds on 
<taxonomicName id="7AEB107E88DE5D8C6FB66AD91CFD65A5" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Galium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Galium" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="008E336D6EEEC43110F3AD06C87B7975" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Galium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="459E95D5F57E9A94BAE320CAED28C02C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type material">
<paragraph id="4D41D1592082F99853706DC0419AB743" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type material.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="185086ACECB3DB40B718FD4FAAD028C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="6B731891E21E7ED0B8CC3555EB76A42E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="70CA6423A818927F91527E9CEAEA32C5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Holotype</emphasis>
: USA. MD
</emphasis>
: Beltsville, 16.iv.1975, S.W.T. Batra, ex. 
<taxonomicName id="2D9F3800D611B0F4F34A611D011E7DAA" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Galium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Galium" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="00376DE790C508000C939A447C202E9B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Galium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (1♂, USNM).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9AF66AA8B2E83F5A39BB075A28C56BB6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="0295C3A4EFDACBA1AE256F136CFC1630" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="83B64FB4D6E7A3A61151EDB62F2BFA89" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Paratypes</emphasis>
: USA. MD
</emphasis>
: Same collection as holotype (1♀, USNM; 1♀, CNC).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BB1D370FDDBE3DD805AC576904862FDF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="281836110275A5D16B3EC700781D229A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3579822A6E19C2775475BE6780DFC869" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The phallus of 
<taxonomicName id="F0ED09B7B2C918D251161BF968CAD3B2" authorityName="Lonsdale" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia galiodes" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galiodes">
<emphasis id="3A9D08B9713E8964FA6A1ED575AD62BD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia galiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(only illustrated in lateral view due to inflexibility of the structure) is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="02682CF7904C7F967F89DDB81734CD4F" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. laticolis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="laticolis">
<emphasis id="11EC8B709B6A7E97C08C53D79C1DA6AE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. laticolis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation id="8A273062453E884D33EF4414570920BD" captionStart="Figures 367–371" captionStartId="F64" captionText="Figures 367 - 371. Ophiomyia laticolis sp. nov., male genitalia 367 hypandrium, ventral 368 hypandrial complex, left lateral 369 phallus, ventral 370 external genitalia, left lateral 371 external genitalia, posterior." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1051.64603.figures367-371" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/572163" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">368</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="832580194318036B49A302D19841492E" captionStart="Figures 367–371" captionStartId="F64" captionText="Figures 367 - 371. Ophiomyia laticolis sp. nov., male genitalia 367 hypandrium, ventral 368 hypandrial complex, left lateral 369 phallus, ventral 370 external genitalia, left lateral 371 external genitalia, posterior." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1051.64603.figures367-371" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/572163" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">369</figureCitation>
), but the distiphallus is narrower, larger and closer to the apex of the basiphallus. Furthermore, the eye is larger, rounder and bulging anteriorly, and the shoulders, fronto-orbital plate and ocellar triangle are pale, although these colour characters may be an artifact of preservation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BAC3000D6F0310A1F4F8F749FE834497" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="5F25A8005E3D23826187A8393F6B8F2A" authorityName="Lonsdale" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia galiodes" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galiodes">
<emphasis id="33FDFF72C83772915EC92ACBD3C87B32" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia galiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar to the European 
<taxonomicName id="DB708756DCC941697A8B98A3DAF24B04" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. galii" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="galii">
<emphasis id="F76E341745CA91FBFD24CB8484B11E06" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. galii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hering, which is the only other 
<taxonomicName id="84A6B9CB465B30BAA4F520BA355C3C0C" authorityName="Braschnikov" authorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9A563329C072D785A14E6C4D212A7119" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known from 
<taxonomicName id="F97F8BA443A229A3450450D942020DEA" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Galium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Galium" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5C13AD931949BC4447EC21F2EBBAA86E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Galium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Spencer, 1990). Their chaetotaxy, wing length and wing vein proportions are nearly the same, and they both have a ventrally curved hypandrium and similar distiphallus. The gena of 
<taxonomicName id="B5F914A0A45F8B65AF4CA0896DEC6FBC" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. galii" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="galii">
<emphasis id="BA641EC2D46280D66B50121AC0161E4D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. galii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is produced at a 45° angle (not 70°) (
<bibRefCitation id="9E0D09E2B10E829137E542E95309FA76" author="Spencer, KA" journalOrPublisher="10, Pt. 5 (g)" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B248" refString="Spencer, KA, 1972. Diptera. Agromyzidae. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects Vol. 10, Pt. 5(g)" title="Diptera. Agromyzidae. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects Vol." year="1972">Spencer 1972</bibRefCitation>
), the basiphallus is longer and less spinulose, and the mesophallus is longer, narrower and extends past the base of the distiphallus (
<bibRefCitation id="232D153F4B6A58D6FC2787533ADF9798" DOI="https://doi.org/10.18655/Agromyzidae" author="Papp, L" journalOrPublisher="Pars Ltd., Hungary. Nagykovacsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B187" refString="Papp, L, Cerny, M, 2015. Agromyzidae (Diptera) of Hungary (Vol. 1). Agromyzinae. Pars Ltd., Hungary. Nagykovacsi, DOI: https://doi.org/10.18655/Agromyzidae" title="Agromyzidae (Diptera) of Hungary (Vol. 1). Agromyzinae." url="https://doi.org/10.18655/Agromyzidae" year="2015">
Papp and 
<normalizedToken id="0BBCE02D4FEC8FD23C8BEA58148A3A7A" originalValue="Černý">Cerny</normalizedToken>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 152).
</paragraph>
